## Notes and Additional Considerations from r2 draft

*The following material comes from an earlier or parallel revision draft (r2 draft). It is preserved here because content costs thought — nothing gets thrown away. Some passages restate the chapter's core ideas in a different voice; others introduce examples or angles not covered above. Read as supplemental exercises for the same discipline.*

### 9.1 Two voices, two melodies

The simplest polyphony: **two independent lines**.

Here is a **descending scale in the upper voice** and an **ascending scale in the lower voice**, both in quarter notes, both starting at the same time. They move in **contrary motion** — one goes up, the other goes down.

```scheme
;; Two-voice contrary motion: upper descends, lower ascends
(transport/tempo 100)

(define (upper-line)
  (base/across-beats
   0 8
   (lambda (b)
     (note/place-at 'quarter (- 72 b) 0.7 b))))

(define (lower-line)
  (base/across-beats
   0 8
   (lambda (b)
     (note/place-at 'quarter (+ 48 b) 0.6 b))))

(upper-line)
(lower-line)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — two independent scales in contrary motion, scheduled via place-at on the same transport grid -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score showing the upper line descending C5→C4 and the lower line ascending C3→C3+octave, quarter notes aligned vertically, barlines every 4 beats. Note-sprites (quarter-value glyphs) placed on each staff, bopping gently in place.]

The voices are **independent**: each calls `base/across-beats` with its own pitch logic. They share the same **beat grid** (both start at beat 0, both end at beat 8), so they align in time — but their **melodic content** is separate.

Run it. You hear two scales at once. The upper voice descends, the lower ascends. Where they cross (around beat 4), you hear a unison or near-unison. At the start and end, you hear wide intervals. The harmony **emerges** from the independence.

---


### 9.2 A simple two-part invention fragment

A **two-part invention** is a piece where both voices are equally important melodies, neither is \"accompaniment.\" Here is a tiny invention fragment: the upper voice plays a four-note **ascending motif**, then rests; the lower voice **answers** with the same motif transposed down an octave, starting on beat 4.

```scheme
;; Two-part invention fragment: call and response
(transport/tempo 108)

(define motif-pitches '(60 62 64 65))  ;; C D E F

(define (upper-voice)
  (let loop ((beats 0)
             (pitches motif-pitches))
    (when (pair? pitches)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car pitches) 0.75 beats)
      (loop (+ beats 0.5) (cdr pitches)))))

(define (lower-voice)
  (let loop ((beats 4)  ;; starts at beat 4
             (pitches (map (lambda (p) (- p 12)) motif-pitches)))
    (when (pair? pitches)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car pitches) 0.7 beats)
      (loop (+ beats 0.5) (cdr pitches)))))

(upper-voice)
(lower-voice)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — call-and-response two-voice fragment using eighth notes and recursive placement -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: C D E F as eighth notes in beats 0–2. Lower staff: silence for 4 beats, then C D E F (octave lower) as eighth notes in beats 4–6. Quarter-note and eighth-note glyphs bopping on their respective staves.]

The upper voice **states** the motif. The lower voice **answers** it, transposed. This is **imitative polyphony** — one voice imitates the other, but at a different time and pitch. The silence in the lower voice (beats 0–4) is part of the structure: it gives the upper voice room to be heard alone, then the lower voice enters.

Run it. You hear: melody, then the same melody lower. They do not overlap in this fragment, but the **pattern** is polyphonic: each voice has its own melodic identity.

---


### 9.3 Overlapping lines — a real two-voice texture

Now we make them **overlap**. The upper voice plays its motif; the lower voice enters **before the upper voice finishes**, so for a few beats, both are sounding.

```scheme
;; Overlapping two-voice texture
(transport/tempo 112)

(define phrase-a '(64 66 67 69 71))  ;; E F# G A B
(define phrase-b '(52 54 55 57 59))  ;; E F# G A B, octave lower

(define (voice-one)
  (let loop ((b 0) (ps phrase-a))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.8 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(define (voice-two)
  (let loop ((b 2) (ps phrase-b))  ;; enters at beat 2
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.7 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(voice-one)
(voice-two)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — overlapping phrases in two voices, quarter-note durations -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: E F# G A B (quarter notes) starting at beat 0. Lower staff: same pitches octave lower, starting at beat 2. Overlap zone (beats 2–5) shows both staves active, note-sprites bopping on both. Barlines every 4 beats.]

Voice one starts at beat 0. Voice two starts at beat 2. From beat 2 to beat 5, **both are sounding**. The overlap creates **intervals**: at beat 2, you hear E (upper) and E (lower), a unison or octave; at beat 3, you hear F# (upper) and F# (lower); and so on. The harmony is a **byproduct** of the two melodic lines.

This is real polyphony. Neither voice is accompaniment. Both are melodies. The listener can follow either one, or hear them together as a texture.

---


### 9.4 A canon at the unison — \"Row, Row, Row Your Boat\"

A **canon** is polyphony where one voice plays the **same melody** as another, but **delayed** in time. \"Row, Row, Row Your Boat\" is a canon: the second voice starts the same tune a few beats after the first.

Here is a tiny original canon fragment: a simple four-note melody, and a second voice entering 4 beats later with the **same melody**.

```scheme
;; A canon at the unison — original melody
(transport/tempo 96)

(define canon-melody
  '((60 1.0)   ;; C, quarter
    (62 1.0)   ;; D, quarter
    (64 1.0)   ;; E, quarter
    (65 2.0))) ;; F, half

(define (play-melody start-beat mel)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (notes mel))
    (when (pair? notes)
      (let ((pitch (car (car notes)))
            (dur (cadr (car notes))))
        (note/place-at 'quarter pitch 0.75 b)
        (loop (+ b dur) (cdr notes))))))

(play-melody 0 canon-melody)   ;; voice 1 at beat 0
(play-melody 4 canon-melody)   ;; voice 2 at beat 4
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — canon at the unison with a simple melody and delayed second voice -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score showing the same melody (C D E F) starting at beat 0 on the upper staff, and again at beat 4 on the lower staff. Overlap zone (beats 4–8) has both voices sounding; note-sprites for both voices visible and bopping. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The first voice plays C D E F (with F held for two beats). The second voice starts at beat 4, playing the **same pitches** in the **same rhythm**. From beat 4 onward, you hear **two voices at once**: the first voice is on F (held), the second voice starts on C. At beat 5, the first voice finishes, the second voice is on D. The overlap creates harmony **not by planning chords, but by the melodic delay**.

Run it. You hear the melody once, then you hear it again overlapping with itself. This is how \"Row, Row, Row Your Boat\" works as a round.

---


### 9.5 A canon at the fifth — transposed entry

A **canon at the fifth** means the second voice plays the same melody, but **transposed up or down a fifth** (7 semitones). This creates richer harmony than a unison canon.

```scheme
;; A canon at the fifth
(transport/tempo 100)

(define melody-line
  '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71 72))  ;; C major scale ascending

(define (transpose pitches interval)
  (map (lambda (p) (+ p interval)) pitches))

(define (play-scale start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

(play-scale 0 melody-line)              ;; voice 1: C major scale
(play-scale 2 (transpose melody-line 7)) ;; voice 2: starts 2 beats later, up a fifth
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — canon at the fifth using transposition and delayed entry -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: C D E F G A B C (eighth notes) starting at beat 0. Lower staff: G A B C D E F# G (eighth notes) starting at beat 2. Overlap zone shows note-sprites bopping on both staves, creating intervals of thirds, fourths, fifths. Barlines every 4 beats.]

Voice one plays a C major scale. Voice two plays the **same scale transposed up 7 semitones** (a perfect fifth), starting 2 beats later. The result: at beat 2, you hear E (voice 1) and G (voice 2), a third; at beat 2.5, you hear F and A, another third; and so on. The harmony is richer than unison, and it **emerged** from the canon structure.

This is how Bach wrote many of his canons: same melody, different pitch level, overlapping.

---


### 9.6 Three voices — a triad in motion

Polyphony is not limited to two voices. Here is **three-voice polyphony**: each voice plays a different note of a **C major triad** (C E G), but each voice **moves independently** in its own rhythm.

```scheme
;; Three voices, each moving through chord tones
(transport/tempo 104)

(define (voice-top)
  (base/across-beats
   0 8
   (lambda (b)
     (note/place-at 'eighth 72 0.7 b))))  ;; C5, steady eighth notes

(define (voice-middle)
  (base/across-beats
   0 8
   (lambda (b)
     (when (= (modulo b 2) 0)  ;; only on even beats
       (note/place-at 'quarter 64 0.65 b)))))  ;; E4, quarter notes

(define (voice-bass)
  (base/across-beats
   0 8
   (lambda (b)
     (when (= (modulo b 4) 0)  ;; only on beats 0, 4, 8
       (note/place-at 'half 48 0.75 b)))))  ;; C3, half notes

(voice-top)
(voice-middle)
(voice-bass)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — three independent voices with different rhythms, forming a triad texture -->`

[VISUAL: Three-staff score. Top staff: steady eighth-note C5 notes (sixteen of them across 8 beats). Middle staff: quarter-note E4 notes on beats 0, 2, 4, 6. Bottom staff: half-note C3 notes on beats 0, 4. Note-sprites bopping at different rates on each staff — top voice jittery (eighths), middle steady (quarters), bass slow (halves). Barlines every 4 beats.]

The top voice is constant, sounding every half beat. The middle voice enters every two beats. The bass voice enters every four beats. Each voice has its **own rhythm**, but they all sound **the same harmony** (a C major triad). The texture is **polyphonic** because each line is independent, even though they are harmonically coordinated.

Run it. You hear a shimmering C major chord where the upper voice is busy, the middle voice punctuates, and the bass anchors. This is how choral music often works: each section (soprano, alto, bass) has its own rhythm, but together they make harmony.

---


### 9.7 Independent rhythms — a hocket

A **hocket** is a medieval polyphonic technique where a melody is **split between two voices**: one voice plays some notes, the other voice plays the **gaps**. The result is a single melody **shared** between two independent lines.

```scheme
;; Hocket: a melody split between two voices
(transport/tempo 120)

(define full-melody
  '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71 72))  ;; C D E F G A B C

(define (voice-odd start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches) (index 0))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (when (odd? index)
        (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.8 b))
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps) (+ index 1)))))

(define (voice-even start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches) (index 0))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (when (even? index)
        (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.8 b))
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps) (+ index 1)))))

(voice-odd 0 full-melody)
(voice-even 0 full-melody)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — hocket texture with melody split between two voices using odd/even index logic -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: C (silent) D (silent) E (silent) F (silent) G (silent) A (silent) B (silent) C — only the odd-index notes (D, F, A, C) are visible. Lower staff: only the even-index notes (C, E, G, B) are visible. The full melody is fragmented across both staves, note-sprites bopping only on the notes each voice plays. Eighth-note glyphs alternating between staves.]

Voice-odd plays notes at odd indices (D, F, A, C). Voice-even plays notes at even indices (C, E, G, B). Together, they play the **full melody**, but **neither voice plays it alone**. The listener hears a continuous scale, but it is being **traded** between two voices.

This technique is rare in modern music, but it was common in medieval polyphony. It is a pure demonstration of **independence**: each voice has its own part, even though the musical result is a single line.

---


### 9.8 A simple fugue subject and answer

A **fugue** is a polyphonic form where a **subject** (a short melody) is stated in one voice, then **answered** by another voice (often a fifth higher or fourth lower), while the first voice continues with a **countersubject** (a new melody that fits against the answer).

Here is a tiny fugue fragment: a four-note subject in the lower voice, then the same subject transposed up a fifth in the upper voice, while the lower voice plays a simple countersubject.

```scheme
;; Fugue fragment: subject and answer with countersubject
(transport/tempo 108)

(define subject '(48 50 52 53))         ;; C D E F (lower voice)
(define answer (map (lambda (p) (+ p 7)) subject))  ;; G A B C (upper voice, up a fifth)
(define countersubject '(36 38 40 41))  ;; C D E F, octave lower (lower voice continues)

(define (play-line start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

;; Lower voice: subject, then countersubject
(play-line 0 subject)
(play-line 4 countersubject)

;; Upper voice: answer (starts at beat 4)
(play-line 4 answer)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — fugue fragment with subject, answer, and countersubject in two voices -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Lower staff: subject (C D E F) in beats 0–3, then countersubject (C D E F, octave lower) in beats 4–7. Upper staff: silence for beats 0–3, then answer (G A B C) in beats 4–7. Overlap zone (beats 4–7) shows both voices active, note-sprites bopping on both staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The lower voice states the subject (beats 0–3). At beat 4, the upper voice **answers** with the same melody transposed up a fifth, and the lower voice **continues** with a new melody (the countersubject). From beat 4 onward, you hear **two independent melodies at once**: the answer in the upper voice, the countersubject in the lower voice.

This is the essence of fugue: **imitation** (the answer imitates the subject) plus **continuation** (the first voice does not stop; it keeps going with new material that fits).

Run it. You hear: subject alone, then subject-as-answer in the upper voice while the lower voice plays a new line. The two voices are independent, but they **fit** harmonically.

---


### 9.9 A three-voice canon — \"Frère Jacques\" structure

A **three-voice canon** (a round with three voices) is a common structure. Each voice plays the same melody, but each enters at a different time. Here is an original three-voice canon fragment using a simple four-note motif.

```scheme
;; Three-voice canon (round structure)
(transport/tempo 100)

(define round-tune
  '((60 1.0)   ;; C, quarter
    (64 1.0)   ;; E, quarter
    (67 1.0)   ;; G, quarter
    (72 2.0))) ;; C, half

(define (sing-tune start-beat tune)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (notes tune))
    (when (pair? notes)
      (let ((pitch (car (car notes)))
            (dur (cadr (car notes))))
        (note/place-at 'quarter pitch 0.7 b)
        (loop (+ b dur) (cdr notes))))))

(sing-tune 0 round-tune)   ;; voice 1
(sing-tune 4 round-tune)   ;; voice 2
(sing-tune 8 round-tune)   ;; voice 3
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — three-voice canon with staggered entries every 4 beats -->`

[VISUAL: Three-staff score. Top staff: C E G C starting at beat 0. Middle staff: C E G C starting at beat 4. Bottom staff: C E G C starting at beat 8. Overlap zones show multiple voices active; note-sprites bopping on all active staves. The same melody cascades down through three voices. Barlines every 4 beats.]

Voice 1 starts at beat 0. Voice 2 starts at beat 4 with the **same melody**. Voice 3 starts at beat 8 with the **same melody**. By beat 8, all three voices are sounding: voice 1 has finished, voice 2 is midway, voice 3 is starting. The harmony is dense — you hear the melody **against itself** at three different time points.

This is how \"Frère Jacques\" works as a round. Each voice is independent (you could follow any one), but together they create a rich polyphonic texture.

---


### 9.10 A walking bass under a melody — two-voice texture

A **walking bass** is a bass line that moves in steady quarter notes (or eighths), usually by step or small intervals, while a melody sounds above it. This is **two-voice polyphony** where the bass has its own melodic logic (it \"walks\"), and the upper voice has a separate melody.

```scheme
;; Walking bass under a melody
(transport/tempo 112)

(define melody-top
  '((72 1.0) (71 0.5) (69 0.5) (67 1.0) (65 1.0) (64 2.0)))

(define bass-walk
  '(48 50 52 53 55 53 52 50))  ;; C D E F G F E D (quarter notes)

(define (play-melody-with-durations start-beat notes)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ns notes))
    (when (pair? ns)
      (let ((pitch (car (car ns)))
            (dur (cadr (car ns))))
        (note/place-at 'quarter pitch 0.75 b)
        (loop (+ b dur) (cdr ns))))))

(define (play-walking-bass start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.7 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(play-melody-with-durations 0 melody-top)
(play-walking-bass 0 bass-walk)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — walking bass line under a melody with independent durations and pitch contours -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: a melody in mixed durations (quarters and halves) with pitches C5 B4 A4 G4 F4 E4. Lower staff: steady quarter-note bass line walking C3 D3 E3 F3 G3 F3 E3 D3. Note-sprites bopping on both staves — upper voice with varied rhythms, lower voice steady and march-like. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The melody has **varied durations** (some notes are longer than others). The bass has **steady quarter notes** in a stepwise pattern. They are independent: the melody's rhythm does not dictate the bass's rhythm, and vice versa. But they **fit** — the intervals between them at each beat create harmony.

Run it. You hear a flowing melody on top, and a steady walking bass underneath. This is the texture of much Baroque music (Bach's two-part inventions often have this character) and jazz (a walking bass is foundational in jazz).

---


### 9.11 A two-voice invention in contrary motion

Here is a longer two-part invention fragment where the voices move in **contrary motion** most of the time: when one goes up, the other goes down. This creates a sense of independence and balance.

```scheme
;; Two-voice invention with contrary motion
(transport/tempo 104)

(define upper-phrase
  '(64 65 67 69 71 72 71 69 67 65 64))  ;; E F G A B C B A G F E

(define lower-phrase
  '(52 50 48 47 45 43 45 47 48 50 52))  ;; E D C B A G A B C D E

(define (play-line-eighth start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

(play-line-eighth 0 upper-phrase)
(play-line-eighth 0 lower-phrase)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — two-voice invention with contrary motion in eighth notes -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: ascending then descending line E F G A B C B A G F E (eighth notes). Lower staff: descending then ascending line E D C B A G A B C D E (eighth notes). The lines mirror each other in opposite directions, creating a symmetrical shape. Note-sprites (eighth-note glyphs) bopping rapidly on both staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The upper voice ascends to C, then descends back to E. The lower voice descends to G, then ascends back to E. They start and end on the **same pitch class** (E, but different octaves), and they move in **opposite directions** throughout. The result is a balanced, symmetrical texture where neither voice dominates.

Contrary motion is a **contrapuntal device**: it helps the ear distinguish the two voices (they are going different ways), and it creates harmonic variety (the intervals between them change constantly).

---


### 9.12 A three-voice chorale texture

A **chorale** is a hymn-like texture with **three or four voices** moving mostly together in rhythm (homophonic), but each voice has its own **pitch line** (so it is also polyphonic in structure). Here is a tiny three-voice chorale fragment: all three voices move in quarter notes, but each has a different pitch at each beat, forming chords.

```scheme
;; Three-voice chorale texture
(transport/tempo 92)

(define soprano '(72 71 69 67 65 64))  ;; C B A G F E
(define alto    '(64 62 60 59 57 55))  ;; E D C B A G
(define bass    '(48 50 52 53 55 57))  ;; C D E F G A

(define (play-voice start-beat pitches vel)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) vel b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(play-voice 0 soprano 0.8)
(play-voice 0 alto 0.7)
(play-voice 0 bass 0.75)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — three-voice chorale with parallel rhythms and independent pitch lines -->`

[VISUAL: Three-staff score. Top staff: C B A G F E (quarter notes). Middle staff: E D C B A G (quarter notes). Bottom staff: C D E F G A (quarter notes). All three staves have the same rhythm (quarter notes aligned vertically), but different pitches. At each beat, a vertical chord is formed. Note-sprites (quarter-note glyphs) bopping in sync across all three staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

All three voices move **together in rhythm** (quarter notes on every beat). But each voice has its **own melodic line**: the soprano descends, the bass ascends, the alto descends in a different pattern. At each beat, the three pitches form a **chord** (beat 0: C E C, an octave + third; beat 1: B D D, etc.).

This is **homophonic polyphony**: the texture is chordal (all voices move together), but each voice is still a **line** (you could sing any one of them as a melody). Much of Bach's chorales are written this way.

---


### 9.13 A four-voice SATB chord progression

**SATB** stands for **Soprano, Alto, Tenor, Bass** — the four standard voices in choral music. Here is a four-voice chord progression: each voice moves independently, but together they form a sequence of chords (I–IV–V–I in C major).

```scheme
;; Four-voice SATB chord progression (I–IV–V–I in C major)
(transport/tempo 88)

;; Chords: C major (C E G C) → F major (C F A C) → G major (B F G D) → C major (C E G C)
(define soprano '(72 72 71 72))  ;; C C B C
(define alto    '(64 65 67 64))  ;; E F G E
(define tenor   '(55 57 59 55))  ;; G A B G
(define bass    '(48 53 55 48))  ;; C F G C

(define (voice start-beat pitches vel)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'half (car ps) vel b)
      (loop (+ b 2) (cdr ps)))))

(voice 0 soprano 0.8)
(voice 0 alto 0.7)
(voice 0 tenor 0.65)
(voice 0 bass 0.75)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — four-voice SATB chord progression with half-note durations -->`

[VISUAL: Four-staff score (SATB). Each staff shows a different voice: soprano (top), alto, tenor, bass (bottom). Each voice plays four half notes, one per chord change. Vertical alignment shows the chords: beat 0 = C major, beat 2 = F major, beat 4 = G major, beat 6 = C major. Note-sprites (half-note glyphs) bopping slowly on all four staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

Each voice has **its own line**: the soprano stays mostly on C, the bass moves C→F→G→C (a typical bass progression), the inner voices (alto and tenor) fill in the harmony. At each beat, the four pitches form a **triad**: C E G C (C major), C F A C (F major with doubled C), B F G D (G major, incomplete — uses F instead of full triad, a voicing choice), C E G C (C major again).

This is **four-voice polyphony**. Each line is independent, but together they create a harmonic progression. This is the foundation of choral writing and much Baroque keyboard music.

---


### 9.14 A syncopated two-voice texture

**Syncopation** is when notes are placed **off the beat** (on weak subdivisions), creating rhythmic tension. Here is a two-voice texture where the upper voice is **syncopated** (notes land between beats) and the lower voice is **on the beat** (steady quarter notes). The voices are independent in **rhythm** as well as **pitch**.

```scheme
;; Syncopated upper voice over steady bass
(transport/tempo 120)

(define (upper-syncopated)
  (let ((beats '(0.5 1.5 2.5 3.5 4.5 5.5 6.5 7.5)))  ;; off-beat eighth notes
    (let loop ((bs beats) (pitch 67))
      (when (pair? bs)
        (note/place-at 'eighth pitch 0.75 (car bs))
        (loop (cdr bs) (+ pitch 1))))))  ;; ascending chromatically

(define (bass-steady)
  (base/across-beats
   0 8
   (lambda (b)
     (note/place-at 'quarter 48 0.7 b))))

(upper-syncopated)
(bass-steady)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — syncopated upper voice against steady bass using off-beat placements -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: eighth notes placed at beats 0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, etc. (between the quarter-note beats), ascending chromatically. Lower staff: steady quarter notes (C3) on every beat. The upper voice's note-sprites (eighth-note glyphs) are shifted right (off the beat), creating visual and rhythmic tension. The lower voice's note-sprites (quarter-note glyphs) are on the beat. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The bass plays on beats 0, 1, 2, 3, etc. — **on the beat**. The upper voice plays at beats 0.5, 1.5, 2.5, 3.5, etc. — **between the beats**. This creates a **syncopated feel**: the upper voice sounds \"late\" or \"displaced\" relative to the bass. The listener hears a steady pulse from the bass, and a floating, off-kilter melody from the upper voice.

Syncopation is a rhythmic form of **independence**: the two voices are not just playing different pitches, they are playing in **different rhythmic positions**. This is foundational in jazz, funk, and much contemporary music.

---


### 9.15 A canon with rhythmic variation

A **canon with rhythmic variation** is where the second voice plays the same **pitches** as the first, but in a **different rhythm** (e.g., the first voice uses quarter notes, the second uses eighth notes). The melodic content is the same, but the **temporal shape** is different.

```scheme
;; Canon with rhythmic variation
(transport/tempo 108)

(define canon-pitches '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71 72))  ;; C major scale

(define (voice-quarters start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(define (voice-eighths start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.7 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

(voice-quarters 0 canon-pitches)   ;; first voice: quarter notes
(voice-eighths 4 canon-pitches)    ;; second voice: eighth notes, starts at beat 4
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — canon with same pitches but different rhythms (quarters vs eighths) -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: C D E F G A B C in quarter notes, beats 0–7. Lower staff: C D E F G A B C in eighth notes, beats 4–7.5. The lower voice moves twice as fast as the upper voice, but plays the same pitches. Overlap zone (beats 4–7) shows both voices active, with the lower voice's note-sprites bopping faster (eighth-note glyphs). Barlines every 4 beats.]

The first voice plays the scale in **quarter notes** (one note per beat). The second voice plays the **same scale** in **eighth notes** (two notes per beat), starting at beat 4. By beat 5, the first voice has played C D E F G (5 notes), and the second voice has played C D (2 notes, but faster). The **pitches** are the same, but the **rhythm** is different.

This is a form of **augmentation and diminution** (a compositional technique where a melody is stretched or compressed in time). The two voices are independent in rhythm, but related in pitch content.

---


### 9.16 A two-voice invention with sequence

A **sequence** is a melodic pattern that **repeats at a different pitch level**. Here is a two-voice invention where both voices play a **sequence**: a short motif that repeats, transposed up by step each time.

```scheme
;; Two-voice invention with sequence
(transport/tempo 112)

(define motif '(0 2 4 5))  ;; a four-note ascending pattern (C D E F as intervals)

(define (play-sequence start-beat root-pitch motif steps)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (root root-pitch) (step 0))
    (when (< step steps)
      (let inner ((offset-b b) (intervals motif))
        (when (pair? intervals)
          (note/place-at 'eighth (+ root (car intervals)) 0.75 offset-b)
          (inner (+ offset-b 0.5) (cdr intervals))))
      (loop (+ b 2) (+ root 2) (+ step 1)))))  ;; transpose up by a whole step each time

(play-sequence 0 60 motif 4)   ;; upper voice: starts on C, repeats 4 times
(play-sequence 2 48 motif 3)   ;; lower voice: starts on C (octave lower), 2 beats later, 3 times
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — two-voice sequence with motif repeating at rising pitch levels -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: motif (C D E F) in eighth notes at beats 0–2, then (D E F# G) at beats 2–4, then (E F# G# A) at beats 4–6, then (F# G# A# B) at beats 6–8. Lower staff: motif (C D E F, octave lower) starting at beat 2, then (D E F# G) at beat 4, then (E F# G# A) at beat 6. The pattern \"climbs\" in both voices, creating a spiral of rising sequences. Note-sprites (eighth-note glyphs) bopping rapidly on both staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The upper voice plays the motif starting on C, then repeats it starting on D (a whole step higher), then on E, then on F#. The lower voice does the same thing, but starting at beat 2 and one octave lower. The result is a **cascading sequence**: both voices are climbing upward in parallel, but offset in time.

Sequences are a common polyphonic technique in Baroque music (Bach uses them extensively in his inventions and fugues). They create **momentum** — the listener hears the pattern repeating and anticipates where it will go next.

---


### 9.17 A fugue subject with a rhythmic countersubject

Here is a fugue fragment where the **countersubject** has a **different rhythm** than the subject, creating rhythmic independence as well as melodic independence.

```scheme
;; Fugue subject with rhythmic countersubject
(transport/tempo 100)

(define subject-pitches '(55 57 59 60))         ;; G A B C (quarter notes)
(define answer-pitches (map (lambda (p) (+ p 5)) subject-pitches))  ;; up a fourth
(define countersubject-pitches '(43 45 47 48 50 52))  ;; G A B C D E (eighth notes)

(define (play-quarters start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(define (play-eighths start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.7 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

;; Lower voice: subject, then countersubject
(play-quarters 0 subject-pitches)
(play-eighths 4 countersubject-pitches)

;; Upper voice: answer at beat 4
(play-quarters 4 answer-pitches)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — fugue with subject in quarters, countersubject in eighths, and answer -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Lower staff: subject (G A B C) in quarter notes, beats 0–3, then countersubject (G A B C D E) in eighth notes, beats 4–6. Upper staff: silence until beat 4, then answer (C D E F) in quarter notes, beats 4–7. Overlap zone (beats 4–6) shows both voices active: upper voice in steady quarters, lower voice in rapid eighths, creating rhythmic counterpoint. Note-sprites (quarter and eighth glyphs) bopping at different rates. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The subject is in **quarter notes**. The countersubject is in **eighth notes** (twice as fast). When the answer enters in the upper voice (also in quarter notes), the lower voice plays the **countersubject** in a faster rhythm. The two voices are independent in **both pitch and rhythm**.

This is a hallmark of fugue: the countersubject is not just a different melody, it is a **different rhythmic character** that complements the subject.

---


### 9.18 A three-voice round with staggered dynamics

Here is a three-voice round where each voice plays the **same melody**, but at **different dynamic levels** (velocities). The first voice is loud, the second is medium, the third is soft. The melody is the same, but the **expressive layering** creates depth.

```scheme
;; Three-voice round with dynamic variation
(transport/tempo 96)

(define round-melody
  '((64 1.0) (65 1.0) (67 1.0) (69 2.0)))  ;; E F G A

(define (sing-with-velocity start-beat melody vel)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (notes melody))
    (when (pair? notes)
      (let ((pitch (car (car notes)))
            (dur (cadr (car notes))))
        (note/place-at 'quarter pitch vel b)
        (loop (+ b dur) (cdr notes))))))

(sing-with-velocity 0 round-melody 0.9)   ;; voice 1: loud
(sing-with-velocity 4 round-melody 0.6)   ;; voice 2: medium
(sing-with-velocity 8 round-melody 0.3)   ;; voice 3: soft
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — three-voice round with different velocities for expressive layering -->`

[VISUAL: Three-staff score. All three staves show the same melody (E F G A), starting at beats 0, 4, and 8 respectively. The note-sprites on the top staff are drawn larger/brighter (loud velocity); the middle staff has medium-brightness sprites; the bottom staff has faint/dim sprites (soft velocity). This creates a visual \"echo\" effect matching the dynamic layering. Barlines every 4 beats.]

All three voices play the **same melody**. But the first voice is **loud** (velocity 0.9), the second is **medium** (velocity 0.6), and the third is **soft** (velocity 0.3). The listener hears the melody three times, but each iteration has a different **presence**: the first is prominent, the second is background, the third is a whisper.

This is **dynamic polyphony** — independence not just in time and pitch, but in **loudness**. It creates a sense of **depth**: the loud voice is in the foreground, the soft voice is in the background, even though they are all sounding at once.

---


### 9.19 A two-voice texture with register separation

**Register** is the pitch range (high vs low). If two voices are in **different registers** (one very high, one very low), the ear can easily distinguish them even if they move in the same rhythm. Here is a two-voice texture with **wide register separation**: one voice in the high treble, one in the low bass.

```scheme
;; Two voices with wide register separation
(transport/tempo 108)

(define high-line '(84 85 87 88 89))  ;; C6 C#6 D#6 E6 F6 (very high)
(define low-line '(36 38 40 41 43))   ;; C2 D2 E2 F2 G2 (very low)

(define (play-line start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(play-line 0 high-line)
(play-line 0 low-line)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — two voices with wide register separation (high treble and low bass) -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score with a wide vertical gap between them. Upper staff (treble clef): very high notes C6 C#6 D#6 E6 F6 (ledger lines above the staff). Lower staff (bass clef): very low notes C2 D2 E2 F2 G2 (ledger lines below the staff). The staves are separated by a large empty space, visually showing the wide pitch gap. Note-sprites (quarter-note glyphs) bopping on both staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The high voice plays in the **sixth octave** (very high, like a piccolo or soprano). The low voice plays in the **second octave** (very low, like a tuba or bass). The gap between them is **four octaves** — a huge range. Even though they move in the same rhythm (quarter notes), the ear hears them as **completely separate layers** because they are so far apart in pitch.

This is a common orchestration technique: place the melody very high, the bass very low, and leave space in the middle. The **separation** makes each voice clear.

---


### 9.20 A two-voice invention with inversion

**Inversion** is a transformation where a melody's intervals are **flipped**: ascending intervals become descending, descending intervals become ascending. Here is a two-voice texture where the second voice is the **inversion** of the first.

```scheme
;; Two-voice texture with inversion
(transport/tempo 104)

(define melody '(60 62 64 65 67 65 64 62 60))  ;; C D E F G F E D C

(define (invert-melody root pitches)
  ;; invert intervals around a root pitch
  (map (lambda (p) (- (* 2 root) p)) pitches))

(define inverted (invert-melody 60 melody))  ;; invert around C (60)

(define (play-line start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

(play-line 0 melody)
(play-line 0 inverted)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — two-voice texture with the second voice as the melodic inversion of the first -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: C D E F G F E D C (ascending then descending arc). Lower staff: C Bb Ab G F G Ab Bb C (descending then ascending arc — the inversion). The two lines are mirror images: where the upper line goes up, the lower goes down, and vice versa. Note-sprites (eighth-note glyphs) bopping on both staves, creating a symmetrical visual pattern. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The original melody ascends C→D→E→F→G, then descends back to C. The inverted melody **descends** C→Bb→Ab→G→F, then **ascends** back to C. Every interval is flipped: the original has +2 (C to D, up a whole step), the inversion has -2 (C to Bb, down a whole step).

Inversion is a **contrapuntal transformation** used extensively in fugues and canons (Bach uses it constantly). It creates **symmetry** and **variety**: the two voices are related, but they move in opposite directions.

---


### 9.21 A rhythmic canon — same rhythm, different pitches

A **rhythmic canon** is where two voices share the same **rhythm**, but have **different pitches**. This is the opposite of the hocket (where voices shared pitches but had different rhythms).

```scheme
;; Rhythmic canon: same rhythm, different pitches
(transport/tempo 112)

(define rhythm '(0.5 0.5 1.0 1.0 2.0))  ;; eighth eighth quarter quarter half

(define melody-a '(60 62 64 65 67))  ;; C D E F G
(define melody-b '(55 57 59 60 62))  ;; G A B C D

(define (play-with-rhythm start-beat pitches durations)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches) (ds durations))
    (when (and (pair? ps) (pair? ds))
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b (car ds)) (cdr ps) (cdr ds)))))

(play-with-rhythm 0 melody-a rhythm)
(play-with-rhythm 0 melody-b rhythm)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — rhythmic canon with two voices sharing rhythm but different pitches -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Both staves have the same rhythmic pattern: eighth eighth quarter quarter half. Upper staff pitches: C D E F G. Lower staff pitches: G A B C D. The note-sprites have the same rhythmic shape on both staves (same glyph types at the same beat positions), but different vertical positions (different pitches). Barlines every 4 beats.]

Both voices play the **same rhythm**: eighth, eighth, quarter, quarter, half. But the **pitches** are different: the upper voice plays C D E F G, the lower voice plays G A B C D (a fourth lower). The rhythmic **alignment** makes the two voices feel **coordinated**, but the pitch **difference** makes them independent melodies.

This is a simple form of **isorhythm** (same rhythm, different pitches), a technique used in medieval and Renaissance polyphony.

---


### 9.22 A four-voice fugue exposition fragment

A **fugue exposition** is the opening section where the **subject** is stated in each voice in turn. Here is a tiny four-voice exposition: the subject appears in the bass, then the tenor, then the alto, then the soprano, each entering a few beats after the previous one.

```scheme
;; Four-voice fugue exposition (subject entries in all voices)
(transport/tempo 96)

(define subject '(48 50 52 53))  ;; C D E F (subject in bass)

(define (transpose pitches interval)
  (map (lambda (p) (+ p interval)) pitches))

(define (play-subject start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(play-subject 0 subject)                       ;; bass: subject at C
(play-subject 4 (transpose subject 7))         ;; tenor: subject at G (up a fifth)
(play-subject 8 (transpose subject 12))        ;; alto: subject at C (up an octave)
(play-subject 12 (transpose subject 19))       ;; soprano: subject at G (up an octave + fifth)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — four-voice fugue exposition with staggered subject entries -->`

[VISUAL: Four-staff score (bass, tenor, alto, soprano from bottom to top). Bass staff: subject (C D E F) starting at beat 0. Tenor staff: subject transposed (G A B C) starting at beat 4. Alto staff: subject (C D E F, octave higher) starting at beat 8. Soprano staff: subject (G A B C, high) starting at beat 12. Each voice enters alone, then overlaps with the next. Note-sprites (quarter-note glyphs) bopping on each staff as it enters. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The bass states the subject (C D E F) alone. At beat 4, the tenor enters with the subject transposed up a fifth (G A B C), while the bass **continues** (it could play a countersubject, but in this minimal example, it is silent after beat 4). At beat 8, the alto enters with the subject an octave higher. At beat 12, the soprano enters with the subject at the highest pitch.

By beat 12, the listener has heard the subject **four times**, each in a different voice and pitch level. This is the essence of a fugue exposition: **imitation** across all voices, building density.

---


### 9.23 A two-voice texture with pedal point

A **pedal point** (or **pedal tone**) is a sustained note in one voice (usually the bass) while other voices move above it. Here is a two-voice texture where the lower voice holds a **long C** (a pedal) while the upper voice plays a melody.

```scheme
;; Pedal point: sustained bass under moving melody
(transport/tempo 100)

(define (pedal-bass)
  (note/place-at 'whole 36 0.7 0))  ;; low C, held for 4 beats

(define melody-over-pedal
  '(60 62 64 65 67 69 71 72))

(define (play-melody-eighth start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

(pedal-bass)
(play-melody-eighth 0 melody-over-pedal)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — pedal point (sustained bass) under a moving melody -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Lower staff: a whole note (C2) sustained across 4 beats (a long horizontal line with a whole-note sprite at the start). Upper staff: a flowing eighth-note melody (C D E F G A B C) across the same 4 beats. The upper voice moves, the lower voice is static. Note-sprites: one large, slow-bopping whole-note glyph on the bass staff; rapid eighth-note glyphs on the upper staff. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The bass plays **one note** (low C) and holds it for the entire duration (a whole note, 4 beats). The upper voice plays a **scale** in eighth notes over that sustained bass. The harmony changes as the melody moves (C over C is a unison, D over C is a ninth, E over C is a third, etc.), but the bass **never changes**.

A pedal point creates **stability** (the bass anchors the harmony) and **tension** (the upper voice creates dissonances against the pedal that eventually resolve). This is common in Baroque organ music and Romantic orchestral music.

---


### 9.24 A three-voice texture with a rhythmic ostinato bass

An **ostinato** is a repeated rhythmic or melodic pattern. Here is a three-voice texture where the bass plays a **rhythmic ostinato** (a short repeating pattern), and the upper two voices play independent melodies over it.

```scheme
;; Three-voice texture with ostinato bass
(transport/tempo 116)

(define bass-ostinato '(48 55 48 55))  ;; C G C G (repeating pattern)

(define (play-ostinato start-beat pattern repeats)
  (let loop ((r 0))
    (when (< r repeats)
      (let inner ((b (+ start-beat (* r (length pattern)))) (ps pattern))
        (when (pair? ps)
          (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.7 b)
          (inner (+ b 1) (cdr ps))))
      (loop (+ r 1)))))

(define melody-top '(72 71 69 67 65 64 62 60))
(define melody-middle '(64 65 67 69 67 65 64 62))

(define (play-line start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(play-ostinato 0 bass-ostinato 4)  ;; bass: repeat 4 times
(play-line 0 melody-top)
(play-line 0 melody-middle)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — three-voice texture with repeating ostinato bass and two independent melodies -->`

[VISUAL: Three-staff score. Bottom staff: repeating pattern C G C G C G C G C G C G C G C G (16 beats total, the ostinato repeats 4 times). Middle staff: melody (E F G A G F E D) in quarter notes. Top staff: melody (C B A G F E D C) in quarter notes. The bass pattern is cyclic and hypnotic; the upper voices are melodic and varied. Note-sprites (quarter-note glyphs) bopping on all three staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The bass plays the **same four-note pattern** (C G C G) four times (16 beats total). The two upper voices play **different melodies** over that repeating bass. The ostinato creates a **groove** — a rhythmic and harmonic foundation that does not change — while the upper voices create **variation** and **interest**.

This texture is foundational in minimalist music (Steve Reich, Philip Glass), African drumming, and much dance music.

---


### 9.25 A canon in augmentation

**Augmentation** is when a melody is played **twice as slow** (note durations are doubled). Here is a canon where the second voice plays the **same melody** as the first, but in **augmentation** (every note is twice as long).

```scheme
;; Canon in augmentation
(transport/tempo 100)

(define melody '(60 62 64 65 67))  ;; C D E F G

(define (play-normal start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'quarter (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 1) (cdr ps)))))

(define (play-augmented start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'half (car ps) 0.7 b)  ;; half notes (twice as long as quarter)
      (loop (+ b 2) (cdr ps)))))

(play-normal 0 melody)
(play-augmented 0 melody)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — canon in augmentation (second voice at half speed) -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: C D E F G in quarter notes (one per beat), spanning beats 0–4. Lower staff: C D E F G in half notes (one per two beats), spanning beats 0–8. The lower voice plays the **same pitches**, but **twice as slow**. Note-sprites: upper staff has quarter-note glyphs (medium bop speed), lower staff has half-note glyphs (slow bop speed). The lower voice is \"stretched out\" in time. Barlines every 4 beats.]

The first voice plays the melody in **quarter notes** (one note per beat). The second voice plays the **same pitches** in **half notes** (one note per two beats). The second voice is **half the speed** of the first. By the time the first voice finishes (beat 5), the second voice is only halfway through (on F).

Augmentation is a **temporal transformation** (like inversion is a pitch transformation). It creates a sense of **layering**: one voice is quick, the other is slow, but they are playing the **same melody**.

---


### 9.26 A two-voice texture with chromaticism

**Chromaticism** is the use of notes outside the diatonic scale (sharps and flats not in the key). Here is a two-voice texture where both voices use **chromatic motion** (moving by half-steps), creating a dense, chromatic polyphony.

```scheme
;; Two-voice chromatic texture
(transport/tempo 108)

(define chromatic-up
  '(60 61 62 63 64 65 66 67 68 69 70 71 72))  ;; C to C, all half-steps

(define chromatic-down
  '(72 71 70 69 68 67 66 65 64 63 62 61 60))  ;; C to C, descending

(define (play-chromatic start-beat pitches)
  (let loop ((b start-beat) (ps pitches))
    (when (pair? ps)
      (note/place-at 'eighth (car ps) 0.75 b)
      (loop (+ b 0.5) (cdr ps)))))

(play-chromatic 0 chromatic-up)
(play-chromatic 0 chromatic-down)
```

`<!-- BUILD: runnable example — two-voice chromatic contrary motion (all half-steps) -->`

[VISUAL: Two-staff score. Upper staff: ascending chromatic scale C C# D D# E F F# G G# A A# B C (eighth notes). Lower staff: descending chromatic scale C B Bb A Ab G Gb F E Eb D Db C (eighth notes). The two lines move in opposite directions, both using every half-step. The result is dense, chromatic, and dissonant. Note-sprites (eighth-note glyphs) bopping rapidly on both staves. Barlines every 4 beats.]

Both voices move by **half-steps** (the smallest interval). The upper voice ascends chromatically, the lower voice descends chromatically. At each beat, the two notes create **chromatic harmony**: minor seconds, major sevenths, tritones — dissonant intervals that create tension.

Chromaticism in polyphony is common in late-Romantic music (Wagner, Mahler) and 20th-century music (Schoenberg). It is harder to follow than diatonic polyphony, but it creates a richer, more complex harmonic texture.

---


### 9.27 A four-voice stretto

A **stretto** is a fugue technique where the subject **overlaps** with itself — the second voice enters **before the first voice finishes**. Here is a four-voice stretto: each voice enters just two beats after the previous one, so all four voices are sounding the subject at once.

")
